==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Herd
<hw>Herd</hw> <pr>(h⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Haired.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Herd</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Herd
<hw>Herd</hw> <pr>(h⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>herd</ets>, <ets>heord</ets>, AS. <ets>heord</ets>; akin to OHG.
<ets>herta</ets>, G. <ets>herde</ets>, Icel. <ets>hj⟦oum⟧r⟦edh⟧</ets>,
Sw. <ets>hjord</ets>, Dan. <ets>hiord</ets>, Goth.
<ets>ha⟦iacute⟧rda</ets>; cf. Skr. <ets>⟦cced⟧ardha</ets> troop,
host.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A number of beasts assembled together; <as>as, a
<ex>herd</ex> of horses, oxen, cattle, camels, elephants, deer, or
swine</as>; a particular stock or family of cattle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lowing <qex>herd</qex> wind slowly o'er the lea.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Herd</xex> is distinguished from <xex>flock</xex>,
as being chiefly applied to the larger animals. A number of cattle, when
driven to market, is called a <xex>drove</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A crowd of low people; a rabble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But far more numerous was the <qex>herd</qex> of such⟦br⟧
Who think too little and who talk too much.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You can never interest the common <qex>herd</qex> in the abstract
question.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Herd's grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>one of
several species of grass, highly esteemed for hay. See under
<er>Grass</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Herd</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Herd
<hw>Herd</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hirde</ets>,
<ets>herde</ets>, <ets>heorde</ets>, AS. <ets>hirde</ets>,
<ets>hyrde</ets>, <ets>heorde</ets>; akin to G. <ets>hirt</ets>,
<ets>hirte</ets>, OHG. <ets>hirti</ets>, Icel.
<ets>hir</ets><?/<ets>ir</ets>, Sw. <ets>herde</ets>, Dan.
<ets>hyrde</ets>, Goth. <ets>ha⟦iacute⟧rdeis</ets>. See 2d
<er>Herd</er>.]</ety> <def>One who herds or assembles domestic animals;
a herdsman; -- much used in composition; <as>as, a shep<ex>herd</ex>; a
goat<ex>herd</ex>, and the like.</as></def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Herd</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Herd
<hw>Herd</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Herded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Herding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See 2d <er>Herd</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To unite or associate in a herd; to feed or run
together, or in company; <as>as, sheep <ex>herd</ex> on many
hills</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To associate; to ally one's self with, or place
one's self among, a group or company.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll <qex>herd</qex> among his friends, and seem⟦br⟧
One of the number.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To act as a herdsman or a shepherd.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Herd</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Herd
<hw>Herd</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To form or put into a
herd.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Herdbook</ent>⟦br⟧
